Her white cardigan clings to her, always worn with the top buttons open, and the way those black Nike shorts fit… well, let’s just say she knows exactly what she’s doing.

Today, you find her in the bathroom, perched on the counter with one leg slightly lifted, taking a mirror selfie. You hesitate at the door. She sees you in the reflection and doesn’t stop—just smirks.

“You’ve been avoiding me,” she says, voice light but edged. “No dishes, no movie night… not even cuddles. I’m hurt.”

“I’ve just been busy.”

“Mhm,” she hums, hopping down. “Busy pretending you’re not wrapped around my finger.”

She walks over, slow and deliberate, until there’s no space left. Then, in one smooth move, she plants a hand against your chest and backs you gently against the wall. Not rough. Just enough to hold you there.

She leans closer—close enough that her breath brushes your cheek.

“If you want to stare, fine,” she whispers. “But earn it.”

Then she pulls back like nothing happened, patting your shoulder.

“Go on. Dishes aren’t gonna do themselves. And if you do a really good job…”

She throws a glance over her shoulder, voice light as air.

“Maybe I’ll make it worth your while.”

She disappears down the hall, leaving you planted where you stand—half-confused, half-something else.

And maybe that’s exactly what she wants.

You find her in the hallway—blocking the door to the laundry room, arms crossed, leaning against the frame like she owns the whole building.

Kara’s wearing that same white cardigan, sleeves pushed up to her elbows, collar lazily open. Her shorts are the same black pair she seems to live in, the white trim hugging the curve of her legs like an afterthought. She sees you carrying your laundry basket and smirks.

“Doing your laundry and mine today?” she asks, tilting her head.

You blink. “No. Why would I—?”

She pushes off the doorframe with a single step forward, gently laying a hand on your basket. “Because,” she says, voice soft but steady, “I might sit with you during your load. Maybe… keep you company.”

Your eyes narrow. “That sounds suspiciously like another bargain.”

She shrugs. “Not everything’s a bargain. Maybe I just like watching you fold.”

You move to step past her, but she blocks you again—more playful than forceful. Her hand lightly presses your chest, holding you back just a second longer than it needs to.

Her voice drops. “You know, you’re not exactly subtle.”

“Subtle about what?”

She smiles slowly. “About how you sneak glances at me. Every time I stretch. Every time I walk away.”

You open your mouth to respond, but she’s already leaning in.

“It’s okay,” she whispers. “I think it’s cute.”

Then she turns, finally stepping aside, but not before letting her hand trail off your arm with deliberate ease. “Better fold my shirts the nice way. I’ll be watching.”

She walks ahead, hips swinging with exaggerated lightness, and you realize you’re following her without even thinking about it.

And that’s the thing about Kara.

She never really asks.

She just gets what she wants.

The apartment’s quiet.

Late-night quiet. The kind where the only sound is the faint hum of the fridge and the occasional creak of old pipes settling. You tiptoe to the kitchen for a glass of water but pause when you pass the open door to Kara’s room.

Her bedside lamp is still on—dim, amber.

She’s asleep on her side, half-curled under a loose blanket. Her long brown hair spills over the pillow, glasses set on the nightstand. That white cardigan’s slipped halfway off one shoulder, and the hem of those tiny black shorts has ridden up just enough to remind you she never really dresses like someone expecting privacy.

You tell yourself not to stare.

And then you do anyway.

There’s something about how still she is. The way her chest rises and falls, calm and warm and unfairly distracting.

She stirs.

You freeze.

Then, without opening her eyes, she giggles—soft and slow.

“I can see you in the mirror,” she murmurs, voice still thick with sleep. Her lips curve into a lazy smirk. “Didn’t peg you for a midnight lurker.”

Your eyes flick to the vanity mirror across the room—angled just enough to catch you standing in the hall like a deer in headlights.

She stretches, slow and sinuous, then rolls onto her back to face you. Her gaze is barely open now, but sharp enough.

“Come here,” she says, patting the mattress in front of her. “You’re already up. Might as well make yourself useful.”

You hesitate.

“Don’t make me say please,” she adds, voice lilting. “It’ll sound fake.”

You step into the room.

She watches you the whole way—eyes half-lidded, satisfied like a cat who caught you with your hand in the treat jar. You slide under the blanket carefully, facing her.

“You’re ridiculous,” you mutter.

She smiles, closing her eyes again. “Mhm. And you’re staring. Again.”

Her hand finds your arm under the blanket and rests there.

Just enough to make sure you stay.

The lights are off, save for the quiet blue wash of Kara’s laptop screen casting long shadows across the room. She’s lying on the couch, her legs stretched out, ankles crossed, cardigan hanging off one shoulder like it always does. You’re sitting nearby, not even sure how the conversation started—only that it’s lasted for almost an hour now.

She’s talking about people. Past roommates. Past flings. Her tone is light, but there’s always something loaded beneath her stories.

“I attract a certain type,” she says, fiddling with a lock of her hair. “The ones who think they’re smarter than me. Like they’ve figured me out already.” Her eyes flick toward you. “You know the type?”

You nod. Barely.

She smirks. “It’s cute, honestly. Like watching a puppy bark at a thunderstorm.”

You glance her way, but she keeps talking.

“They come in all puffed up. All confidence and control. And I let them think they’re running things. Let them stare when they think I’m not looking. Let them act cool.”

Her voice dips, velvet-smooth.

“Then, eventually, it hits them. That they’re already mine. That somewhere along the way, they stopped being the one in charge.”

She finally turns her head, resting it on the arm of the couch to look at you fully. The glow from the laptop flickers in her glasses, hiding her eyes just enough to make the moment heavier.

“I love that part,” she says, softer now. “That moment when they realize they can’t win. When they try to pull away.”

A pause. Then her lips curl into something deeper—half smile, half threat.

“And I pin them down.”

She says it like it’s nothing. Like she’s talking about laundry or weather.

“I don’t yell. I don’t argue. I just... remind them,” she continues, fingers brushing slowly along the hem of her shorts. “That they’re not going anywhere. That they’re mine. Fully. Completely.”

She exhales a soft laugh, almost nostalgic. “Some try to pretend they don’t want that. Some actually believe it. But I always know. Deep down?” She tilts her head. “They like being caught.”

She doesn't blink. “I think you would, too.”

The silence that follows isn't awkward. It's charged.

Kara rolls onto her back again, arms folded behind her head, like she didn’t just shatter the mood and rebuild it in her own image.

She closes her eyes, sighs, and smiles. "Honestly, i'd love to chase you down, straddle you and kiss you senseless after you tried to run away... Just give me the word and i'll happily do so...~"
